1
00:00:05,946 --> 00:00:08,456
Welcome to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:08,777 --> 00:00:11,392
Today we will discuss collisional
transport in plasmas.

3
00:00:12,004 --> 00:00:14,318
Even if collisions play 
a relative minor role

4
00:00:14,318 --> 00:00:15,627
in plasmas that are hot,

5
00:00:15,627 --> 00:00:19,211
which is the case of course
of plasmas for magnetic fusion,

6
00:00:19,211 --> 00:00:21,813
they're crucial for determining 
the plasma resistivity

7
00:00:21,813 --> 00:00:23,845
and the transport of particles and heat.

8
00:00:24,579 --> 00:00:26,670
The former characterize 
uniform plasmas,

9
00:00:26,670 --> 00:00:29,458
as you have seen in detail
in the first parts of this course.

10
00:00:30,243 --> 00:00:32,269
But today we'll address the latter,

11
00:00:32,728 --> 00:00:36,162
which characterize non-uniform plasmas.

12
00:00:36,601 --> 00:00:39,294
In particular, we will look at 
how collisions determine transport

13
00:00:39,294 --> 00:00:42,992
in real space of particles and heat.

14
00:00:43,934 --> 00:00:46,846
We will start with a general discussion
on the <i>random walk</i>

15
00:00:47,005 --> 00:00:49,178
and its relation to classical diffusion,

16
00:00:49,178 --> 00:00:50,994
both as a general reminder,

17
00:00:51,625 --> 00:00:53,375
and because this approach

18
00:00:53,375 --> 00:00:56,515
will enable us to treat
the complex situation

19
00:00:56,515 --> 00:01:00,101
of the magnetically confined
fusion plasmas, in a very simple way.

20
00:01:00,581 --> 00:01:03,843
We'll prove that the heuristic 
random-walk model

21
00:01:03,843 --> 00:01:06,114
does indeed correspond
to a diffusion process

22
00:01:06,727 --> 00:01:09,388
in the case of an unmagnetized plasma.

23
00:01:09,530 --> 00:01:12,365
And we will see how the plasma sets up
an intrinsic electric field

24
00:01:12,365 --> 00:01:15,029
to maintain quasi-neutrality
called the <i>ambipolar field</i>

25
00:01:15,488 --> 00:01:18,924
and how this later diffusion
that is equal for ions and electrons.

26
00:01:19,061 --> 00:01:21,634
This is the so-called <i>ambipolar diffusion</i>.

27
00:01:22,362 --> 00:01:25,060
We will treat the case 
of the magnetized plasmas

28
00:01:25,060 --> 00:01:27,164
on the basis of the random-walk concepts,

29
00:01:27,164 --> 00:01:30,185
so a very simple mathematical treatment,

30
00:01:30,185 --> 00:01:33,102
and we will distinguish
particle and heat transport,

31
00:01:33,756 --> 00:01:36,251
and parallel and perpendicular directions

32
00:01:36,251 --> 00:01:38,824
with respect to the ambient 
magnetic field.

33
00:01:39,463 --> 00:01:42,219
Naturally, for a magnetized plasma

34
00:01:42,219 --> 00:01:45,983
cross-field transport 
is the crucial element for confinement.

35
00:01:47,023 --> 00:01:50,399
Just to start reminding ourselves
what a random walk is,

36
00:01:50,755 --> 00:01:55,902
you can see here two simulations
of a 2D situation

37
00:01:56,670 --> 00:02:01,826
in which we simulate on the left
the evolution of a single particle

38
00:02:02,206 --> 00:02:05,168
which undertakes statistically 
independent steps.

39
00:02:05,984 --> 00:02:07,812
Each step has the same size,

40
00:02:07,812 --> 00:02:11,015
but of course in a different,
randomly chosen direction.

41
00:02:11,710 --> 00:02:13,939
As opposed to the right-hand side

42
00:02:13,939 --> 00:02:18,125
where you see a movie that simulates
the evolution of many particles

43
00:02:18,732 --> 00:02:21,746
each of which undergoes a random walk.

44
00:02:21,746 --> 00:02:25,583
So you can see the different steps
on the left,

45
00:02:26,001 --> 00:02:29,682
and on the right, 
the spreading of a cloud

46
00:02:29,826 --> 00:02:31,949
in a sense that represents

47
00:02:31,949 --> 00:02:36,224
the spreading
of the initially close particles

48
00:02:36,224 --> 00:02:38,845
under the influence of that random walk.

49
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:43,283
Although the average displacement is zero,

50
00:02:43,283 --> 00:02:46,994
the mean square displacement
as we will see immediately

51
00:02:47,010 --> 00:02:48,720
is actually non-zero,

52
00:02:48,770 --> 00:02:52,119
and that's the crucial element
for assessing transport.

53
00:02:53,542 --> 00:02:57,024
Having briefly seen 
the two-dimensional simulations

54
00:02:57,024 --> 00:02:59,271
now we are ready for a very simple

55
00:02:59,271 --> 00:03:02,923
one-dimensional calculation 
of the random walk.

56
00:03:03,330 --> 00:03:06,504
Again, we consider 
statistically independent steps

57
00:03:06,504 --> 00:03:10,838
ξi each of size ξ.

58
00:03:10,884 --> 00:03:13,118
So we can see what happens 
after N steps.

59
00:03:15,721 --> 00:03:17,643
After N steps, the displacement

60
00:03:17,702 --> 00:03:21,324
will be simply the sum 
of the steps undertaken.

61
00:03:24,773 --> 00:03:27,015
The average displacement will be zero,

62
00:03:27,015 --> 00:03:31,741
and average here means 
'taken over many possible random walks'.

63
00:03:32,097 --> 00:03:34,569
It doesn't mean 'in time '
for the same particle.

64
00:03:35,910 --> 00:03:37,949
But, as we said before,

65
00:03:38,463 --> 00:03:43,545
the average of the square 
of the displacement is not zero.

66
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:47,680
And we'll evaluate it in a simple way.

67
00:03:50,750 --> 00:03:52,697
It will be equal to the sum

68
00:03:52,697 --> 00:03:56,328
of the average of the square
of each step

69
00:03:56,328 --> 00:04:00,410
plus the crossed terms.

70
00:04:03,771 --> 00:04:06,844
But the crossed terms actually
do not contribute

71
00:04:07,126 --> 00:04:10,323
because as we said, all the steps
are statistically independent.

72
00:04:12,306 --> 00:04:13,829
Therefore the average of that product

73
00:04:13,829 --> 00:04:16,080
is equal to the product 
of the two averages

74
00:04:16,529 --> 00:04:18,580
which of course is zero.

75
00:04:20,833 --> 00:04:25,164
So we only end up with N times

76
00:04:25,164 --> 00:04:29,613
where N
is the number of steps undertaken

77
00:04:29,642 --> 00:04:33,408
times ξ² where ξ

78
00:04:33,600 --> 00:04:36,683
is the size of each step.

79
00:04:37,132 --> 00:04:40,003
If we define the inter-collision
time as τ

80
00:04:43,017 --> 00:04:46,669
that means that the number of steps N

81
00:04:47,496 --> 00:04:50,234
is equal to the total time 
divided by τ

82
00:04:50,335 --> 00:04:54,650
we can evaluate 
the mean square displacement as follows:

83
00:04:56,245 --> 00:05:06,205
< x² > is equal to N ξ² = t/τ ξ²
<i>[ Note: x̅ = < x > ]</i>

84
00:05:06,268 --> 00:05:09,322
which is equal to the typical 
squared velocity

85
00:05:09,322 --> 00:05:16,466
averaged <v²> τ t.

86
00:05:17,258 --> 00:05:20,716
And this product, <v²> τ

87
00:05:20,852 --> 00:05:24,772
can be called 
D : <i>diffusion coefficient.</i>

88
00:05:26,065 --> 00:05:33,494
So D = <v²> τ
as we have just defined,

89
00:05:34,141 --> 00:05:39,355
or ξ² / τ

90
00:05:40,262 --> 00:05:44,455
and that is even simpler conceptually

91
00:05:44,455 --> 00:05:47,606
and also to apply 
to the different situations

92
00:05:47,606 --> 00:05:52,496
because that means we have simply 
the product of the typical step size

93
00:05:53,627 --> 00:05:57,324
in our random walk, squared,

94
00:05:58,294 --> 00:06:03,367
times a typical collision frequency

95
00:06:04,294 --> 00:06:08,571
which is of course the inverse
of the intercollision time.

96
00:06:09,710 --> 00:06:14,428
Here's the idea that we will apply
to much more complicated situations,

97
00:06:14,741 --> 00:06:17,697
those that actually are needed
for fusion.

98
00:06:18,758 --> 00:06:23,545
If we identify a characteristic time
or equivalently a collision frequency

99
00:06:23,545 --> 00:06:27,634
and a typical step size 
in various situations we need to assess,

100
00:06:28,231 --> 00:06:30,290
we can evaluate the diffusion coefficient.

101
00:06:32,140 --> 00:06:35,371
For example, if we take electrons
that are colliding with ions

102
00:06:35,371 --> 00:06:37,405
in a fully ionized plasma,

103
00:06:37,405 --> 00:06:41,298
we can say the characteristic frequency
is that of the momentum exchange,

104
00:06:41,298 --> 00:06:45,404
<νe/i> as you have seen 
in previous parts of the course.

105
00:06:45,404 --> 00:06:49,649
I remind you that in this case
the average symbol indicates

106
00:06:49,649 --> 00:06:53,883
an average over 
the Maxwellian distribution in the plasma.

107
00:06:55,106 --> 00:06:56,658
And we have a step size

108
00:06:56,658 --> 00:07:00,487
that corresponds to the mean free path
for such collisions.

109
00:07:00,860 --> 00:07:03,854
Mean free path is always one 
over the density of the targets

110
00:07:04,361 --> 00:07:07,516
times the cross section for that process.

111
00:07:08,048 --> 00:07:11,233
And that's corresponding
to the thermal speed

112
00:07:11,233 --> 00:07:16,796
for the electrons, divided again 
by the characteristic frequency

113
00:07:16,796 --> 00:07:19,195
for the momentum exchange,
average of the distribution.

114
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:23,723
So we get a simple evaluation
of the diffusion coefficient

115
00:07:23,723 --> 00:07:28,130
which is the square of the thermal speed
for the electrons in this case,

116
00:07:28,130 --> 00:07:30,676
divided by the effective 
collision frequency

117
00:07:30,676 --> 00:07:32,359
for the exchange of momentum.

118
00:07:33,241 --> 00:07:36,555
So this will help us 
in a number of situations.

119
00:07:36,555 --> 00:07:39,761
The question is: can we verify,
at least in a simple case

120
00:07:39,761 --> 00:07:41,013
that this approach works,

121
00:07:41,013 --> 00:07:44,770
and that D has indeed
the meaning of a diffusion coefficient.

122
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:49,397
And I propose to do that in the case

123
00:07:49,397 --> 00:07:52,438
of an unmagnetized steady-state plasma

124
00:07:52,438 --> 00:07:53,488
with uniform temperature.

125
00:07:53,488 --> 00:07:55,284
So as simple as we can get,

126
00:07:55,284 --> 00:08:01,264
but yet a typical case in which
we'll try to interpret D

127
00:08:01,264 --> 00:08:02,923
as a real diffusion coefficient.

128
00:08:02,930 --> 00:08:07,797
We start by the equation of motion
for electrons or ions.

129
00:08:10,793 --> 00:08:16,231
So the mass times the acceleration
is of course equal to the electrical force

130
00:08:16,353 --> 00:08:17,935
qj E,

131
00:08:18,413 --> 00:08:23,922
plus the pressure force
which is -∇p

132
00:08:23,972 --> 00:08:25,652
divided by the density [nj]

133
00:08:27,769 --> 00:08:34,400
plus the friction term which is
minus the mass times the velocity

134
00:08:34,423 --> 00:08:37,987
times an effective collision frequency.

135
00:08:38,051 --> 00:08:41,102
So this is my friction term.

136
00:08:41,471 --> 00:08:45,609
I impose steady-state,
so no time derivatives,

137
00:08:46,129 --> 00:08:49,519
I consider uniform temperature

138
00:08:50,259 --> 00:08:51,588
for any species.

139
00:08:51,918 --> 00:08:56,700
That means that ∇pj
is simply the temperature

140
00:08:56,700 --> 00:09:00,089
times the gradient of the density [∇nj]

141
00:09:02,032 --> 00:09:03,997
So with these assumptions,

142
00:09:04,293 --> 00:09:07,175
I can evaluate my equation of motion,

143
00:09:08,023 --> 00:09:11,569
so no time derivative,
so that's zero on the left

144
00:09:12,547 --> 00:09:17,475
equals to qj Ej, 
minus the pressure term

145
00:09:17,475 --> 00:09:20,637
simplified for uniform temperatures,

146
00:09:20,757 --> 00:09:23,839
and the friction term.

147
00:09:24,747 --> 00:09:26,731
That means I can have

148
00:09:27,857 --> 00:09:32,774
a steady-state velocity field,
which is vj,

149
00:09:32,867 --> 00:09:37,795
that I can express with two terms:

150
00:09:38,596 --> 00:09:41,304
the first term proportional 
to the electric field,

151
00:09:43,551 --> 00:09:46,432
and the second term proportional
to the gradient of the density.

152
00:09:47,260 --> 00:09:52,436
The first term has a coefficient
which is related to the mobility.

153
00:09:53,647 --> 00:09:58,747
I say <i>related</i> because 
it's a pretty much the mobility

154
00:09:58,747 --> 00:10:03,214
except the mobility [μj] is defined 
with an absolute value of the charge,

155
00:10:03,214 --> 00:10:07,464
there is no sign,
as the charge in absolute value

156
00:10:07,464 --> 00:10:09,348
divided by the mass

157
00:10:09,409 --> 00:10:14,628
times the collision frequency, mj νj

158
00:10:15,388 --> 00:10:19,184
The other term has a coefficient in front,

159
00:10:20,064 --> 00:10:24,953
which is called the diffusion coefficient.

160
00:10:25,477 --> 00:10:31,301
For the moment 
it's a relatively arbitrary definition

161
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:35,307
but we will converge towards
an inerpretation for both cases.

162
00:10:36,165 --> 00:10:37,770
So that's Dj

163
00:10:40,652 --> 00:10:45,084
which is the thermal speed
for species vj² divided by

164
00:10:45,084 --> 00:10:47,037
the collision frequency once more.

165
00:10:47,131 --> 00:10:52,382
Of course the thermal speed squared
is the ratio of the temperature

166
00:10:52,382 --> 00:10:54,021
divided by the mass.

167
00:10:56,379 --> 00:11:00,026
We note, as actually Einstein did,

168
00:11:00,026 --> 00:11:08,636
that the ratio of the mobility coefficient
divided by the diffusion coefficent

169
00:11:08,636 --> 00:11:14,031
is simply equal to the ratio
of the charge by the temperature.

170
00:11:15,209 --> 00:11:18,341
the so-called <i>Einstein relation.</i>

171
00:11:20,009 --> 00:11:24,962
Now we're interested in flux
which we call Γj

172
00:11:25,085 --> 00:11:26,226
with species j.

173
00:11:26,281 --> 00:11:31,479
That's the density times the velocity.

174
00:11:32,258 --> 00:11:37,062
So we can use the expression 
with the velocity we have just found.

175
00:11:37,785 --> 00:11:42,955
And we get nj
times the sign of the charge,

176
00:11:44,736 --> 00:11:48,410
times µj, times electric field,

177
00:11:49,642 --> 00:11:55,407
minus the diffusion coefficient,
times the gradient of the density.

178
00:11:56,246 --> 00:12:00,164
Now consider for a moment
zero electric field,

179
00:12:01,786 --> 00:12:04,814
in this case we have Γj

180
00:12:06,217 --> 00:12:08,638
the flux is equal to

181
00:12:10,173 --> 00:12:13,482
the diffusion coefficient,
with a minus sign in front,

182
00:12:14,084 --> 00:12:15,957
times the gradient of the density

183
00:12:16,053 --> 00:12:17,983
This is the so-called <i>Fick's Law.</i>

184
00:12:19,185 --> 00:12:22,871
It tells us that particles tend
to move down a density gradient,

185
00:12:22,871 --> 00:12:25,445
which is a very general property 
of course.

186
00:12:25,736 --> 00:12:28,359
Now we use the continuity equation

187
00:12:30,224 --> 00:12:33,183
without sources or sinks.

188
00:12:35,094 --> 00:12:40,525
So that's ∂nj/∂t
plus the divergence of the flux

189
00:12:41,501 --> 00:12:43,991
for species j equal to zero,

190
00:12:45,123 --> 00:12:49,888
and we use that to combine,

191
00:12:51,008 --> 00:12:56,269
to be combined with the definition
of Γj or in fact with the result of Γj

192
00:12:56,269 --> 00:13:00,930
as a function of the gradient
of the density.

193
00:13:02,147 --> 00:13:06,814
So that we come to a final equation,
which will be the diffusion equation.

194
00:13:07,469 --> 00:13:08,741
Let's do that.

195
00:13:11,855 --> 00:13:17,230
Now I assume here that Dj is a constant

196
00:13:20,180 --> 00:13:25,924
so that I can take it out 
of the differential operator.

197
00:13:26,197 --> 00:13:30,113
This is just for the purpose of showing
the final result,

198
00:13:30,127 --> 00:13:33,257
of course in real situations
this may not be the case.

199
00:13:34,034 --> 00:13:37,081
And I get to the expression of

200
00:13:37,631 --> 00:13:43,326
∂nj /∂t -Dj,
diffusion coefficient

201
00:13:44,217 --> 00:13:49,424
times the second spatial derivative 
